# Spring Boot Ultimate Production Rules - Architecture (15 Rules)

Stack baseline for this ruleset: Spring Boot, Java 17+, PostgreSQL, Redis, Docker, Kubernetes.

1. Use Clean Architecture or Hexagonal Architecture as the default system shape.
2. Enforce strict layering: Controller -> Application Service -> Domain Service -> Repository -> Infrastructure.
3. Keep controllers thin; controllers only validate, delegate, and map responses.
4. Keep domain logic independent from frameworks, HTTP, persistence, and messaging details.
5. Apply dependency inversion; inner layers must not depend on outer layers.
6. Prohibit cyclic dependencies between modules at compile time.
7. Organize code by business capability (feature/module first), not technical folder dumping.
8. Define explicit module boundaries and public contracts for inter-module calls.
9. Use DTOs for inbound/outbound API contracts; never expose JPA entities to API consumers.
10. Isolate external integrations (payment, notification, third-party APIs) in infrastructure adapters.
11. Use domain events for cross-module side effects to reduce coupling.
12. Keep shared kernel minimal (`common`) and ban business logic leakage into shared utilities.
13. Require backward-compatible evolution for public APIs and inter-service contracts.
14. Make non-functional requirements explicit: latency, throughput, availability, RTO/RPO.
15. Design for operability first: health checks, graceful shutdown, and production-safe defaults.
